          "body": "The Chronicler's account of the battle is deliberately structured to keep Yahweh as the subject. 'The Lord routed the Ethiopians before Asa and before Judah' (14:12) — Asa and Judah are the spatial reference points, not the agents. 'They were shattered before the Lord and before His army' (14:13) — the Hebrew machaneh (army/camp) attributed to Yahweh echoes the Exodus tradition where the divine warrior leads a heavenly host (Exodus 14:24; Joshua 5:14). The scope of the victory extends beyond the battlefield: surrounding cities are despoiled because 'the dread of the Lord had fallen on them' (14:14), and the livestock tents of the entire region are stripped (14:15). This is not a battle result; it is a theophanic event. Yahweh's pachad — the overwhelming divine terror that paralyzed Jericho (Joshua 2:9) and Egypt (Exodus 15:16) — now falls on the Cushite coalition and its neighbors. The return to Jerusalem (14:15) closes the chapter with the army enriched and the theology of 14:7 empirically confirmed: seeking produces rest, and when rest is threatened, the God who gave it defends it."
