        "number": 2,
        "title": "Rest as covenantal gift — the theology of seeking and its fruit",
        "range": "14:6-8",
        "excerpt": "He built fortified cities in Judah, since the land was undisturbed, and there was no one at war with him during those years, because the Lord had given him rest.",
        "body": "The building program of verses 6-7 is frequently read as political prudence — a king using a period of peace to strengthen infrastructure. The Chronicler will not permit this reading. He provides not one but two explanatory clauses for the peace (shaqat in v.6; nuach in v.6), and then hands the microphone to Asa himself in verse 7 to make the theology explicit. The political reading evaporates the moment Asa speaks: 'The land is still ours because we have sought the Lord our God.'\n\nThe two Hebrew words for rest are doing distinct theological work. *Shaqat* (vv. 1, 5, 6) describes the observable condition — the land is quiet, undisturbed, free from military threat. It is the state the historian can verify from the record. *Nuach* (vv. 6, 7) is the covenantal word — the rest that God grants to those in relationship with Him. Deuteronomy 12:10 uses nuach of the rest God will give in the promised land when Israel is faithful; 1 Chronicles 22:9 applies the same word to Solomon, whose name the Chronicler etymologizes as 'man of rest.' Asa's nuach places him in a line of covenant-obedient kings who receive the same gift.\n\nAsa's speech in verse 7 is the chapter's theological center of gravity. 'The land is still ours because we have sought the Lord our God; we have sought Him, and He has given us rest on every side.' The repetition of 'sought' (darash, twice) is emphatic in the Hebrew — it is not stylistic variation but insistence. The seeking is the cause; the rest and the land-holding are the effects. Asa is doing what a faithful leader must do: articulating the theological premise of the building program so that the workers understand they are not constructing security but responding to a security already given.\n\nThe army inventory of verse 8 functions as a narrative transition, but it also serves the Chronicler's purpose in a subtle way. 580,000 troops is a formidable number — the reader should feel impressed. The impression is immediately necessary for the counter-impression of verse 9 (one million), which will make Asa's prayer the only coherent response. The army's existence is not a contradiction of the seeking-theology; it is the normal provision of a nation at peace. The problem arises not from having an army but from trusting it instead of seeking God — a temptation that will consume Asa in chapter 16.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nuach* (to give rest) is the covenantal rest word; compare its use in 1 Chronicles 22:9 (Solomon's rest) and Deuteronomy 12:10 (the land's rest when Israel is faithful). *Shaqat* (to be quiet, undisturbed) is the observable political condition. *Darash* (seek) repeated twice in v.7 — emphatic construction, not stylistic filler."
