        "excerpt": "So the Lord routed the Ethiopians before Asa and before Judah, and the Ethiopians fled…they were shattered before the Lord and before His army.",
        "body": "The battle report in verses 12-15 is not a military history; it is a theophanic event narrated in military categories. The Chronicler assigns the decisive action to Yahweh in the grammar of every clause. 'The Lord routed the Ethiopians before Asa and before Judah' (v.12) — Asa and Judah are prepositional phrases, the spatial setting before which the rout occurs, not its agents. 'They were shattered before the Lord and before His army' (v.13) — the machaneh (army/camp) attributed to Yahweh is the Old Testament's language for the heavenly host, the divine warrior's celestial force (cf. Joshua 5:14; 2 Kings 6:17). Judah is pursuing; Yahweh is routing.\n\nThe scope of the victory is deliberately extended beyond the battlefield. Asa and the army pursue to Gerar (v.13); the surrounding cities are despoiled because 'the dread of the Lord had fallen on them' (v.14); the livestock camps of the entire region are stripped (v.15). This expansion is the Chronicler's way of signaling that the battle was not a tactical engagement but a divine declaration. The pachad Yahweh — the terror of God — is the same overwhelming divine fear that paralyzed Jericho before Joshua (Joshua 2:9), that fell on the nations at the Exodus (Exodus 15:14-16), and that Deuteronomy 2:25 describes as God's eschatological weapon: 'This day I will begin to put the dread and fear of you upon the peoples.' Asa's victory participates in a pattern that stretches from Sinai to the conquest to the Davidic kingdom.\n\nThe plunder (shalal, v.13; bizzah, v.14) is not a trophy of Judah's military skill but a sign that Yahweh's battle-god victory is total. In ancient Near Eastern warfare, plunder confirmed whose deity had triumphed. The Chronicler is making precisely this theological point: the wealth of Zerah's coalition transfers to Judah not because Judah was the better army but because Yahweh answered the prayer of verse 11. The same principle governs the Exodus plunder (Exodus 3:22; 12:36) and the spoils of Jericho (Joshua 6:24).\n\nThe chapter closes with the army's return to Jerusalem (v.15) — a geographic completion that is also a theological one. The city of David, where the chapter opened with Abijah's burial and Asa's accession (v.1), receives back the army that went out 'in Your name' (v.11) and returns with the confirmation that the name held. The Chronicler's invitation to the reader is clear: the theology Asa articulated in verse 7 ('we have sought the Lord and He has given us rest') is not prosperity-gospel optimism but covenant reality. Seeking, when tested by crisis and expressed in prayer, produces a victory that exceeds any military calculation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nagaph* (to smite/rout, v.12) — often used of divine striking in holy-war contexts (Exodus 12:23; Numbers 14:42). *Machaneh* (army/camp, v.13) — used of the divine host in Genesis 32:2 and 2 Kings 6:17. *Pachad Yahweh* (terror of the Lord, v.14) — the divine-warfare tradition's signature weapon, anchored in Exodus 15:16 and Deuteronomy 2:25."
